# Mutable External State in React Components

External systems (AI SDK streaming, WebSocket handlers, imperative libraries, shared stores) can mutate objects that React holds by reference. This silently breaks memoization because `prev` and `next` point to the same mutated object.

## React.memo Comparators

When editing `React.memo` comparators, check whether props include data from external mutable sources. Never rely solely on deep content equality for actively-updating data — check status flags first and bail early.

Canonical pattern (`app/components/chat/message.tsx` line 73):

```typescript
if (next.status === "streaming" && next.isLast) return false
```

Always place the streaming bail-out **before** any content equality checks.

## AI SDK Message Parts Are Mutable During Streaming

The `parts` array and nested objects (`reasoningPart.text`, `textPart.text`, `toolPart.state`) are mutated in place during streaming. The first `write()` call uses `pushMessage` (no clone), so the mutable object leaks into React state. Always assume parts content is **unstable** during `status === "streaming"`.

## Creating New Memoized Streaming Components

Default to `React.memo(Component)` **without** a custom comparator — let React's shallow equality handle it. Only add a custom comparator if profiling shows a measurable performance problem, and always include the streaming bail-out:

```typescript
const MyComponent = React.memo(function MyComponent(props: Props) {
  // ...
}, (prev, next) => {
  if (next.status === "streaming" && next.isLast) return false
  // ... other checks only after the bail-out
})
```

## Diagnostic Hint

If a memoized component isn't re-rendering when expected during streaming, check `Object.is(prev.parts, next.parts)` in the comparator. If `true`, the data source is mutating in place — the reference never changed. See `.agents/troubleshooting/streaming-ui-rendering.md` for the full diagnostic flow.
